BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:data-society-senior-researcher-ai-civics-2026@artificialnouveau.github.
 io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260730
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260731
SUMMARY:Deadline: Senior Researcher\, AI Civics
DESCRIPTION:Data & Society\, the independent nonprofit studying the social 
 implications of data-centric technologies and automation\, is hiring a Sen
 ior Researcher for AI Civics\, a newly launched two-year programme on civi
 c action and community control over AI. The programme aims to amplify the 
 tools of civic participation so the public can directly shape the role AI 
 plays in society\, surfacing civic tools people can use to exert political
  power over AI systems and tech platforms at community level. It co-create
 s toolkits and training resources with anchor partner organisations\, diff
 uses them through a train-the-trainer model\, and builds toward a national
  civic coalition demanding democratic accountability over AI. The Senior R
 esearcher is a subject-matter expert and lead contributor\, drawing primar
 ily on participatory methods and especially participatory action research\
 , and is responsible for one or more inter-organisational partnerships wit
 h national partner organisations working in K-12 education\, labour\, fait
 h or advocacy. Responsibilities span cultivating and stewarding relationsh
 ips with partner staff\, community members and leaders and public sector w
 orkers\; leading collaborative relationships with an anchor partner and it
 s local members for the co-creation and diffusion of AI Civics resources\;
  co-developing and iterating toolkits\, facilitation guides and training c
 urricula and running piloting\, feedback and revision cycles\; producing c
 ase studies\, educational materials\, templates\, reports\, academic publi
 cations\, lectures and public writing\; supporting facilitation preparatio
 n for co-design workshops\, train-the-trainer sessions and participatory r
 esearch activities\; developing research questions\, strategies and new ex
 ternal partnerships with the Program Director\; network communications\; p
 articipating in fundraising\, including grant applications and materials f
 or the Development Team\; and contributing to the intellectual life of the
  organisation. REQUIRED: graduate degree or equivalent\; expertise in one 
 or more sectors of interest to the programme (K-12 education\, labour\, fa
 ith groups\, or another institutional pillar of civic life as it relates t
 o data-centric technologies and AI)\; 7 to 10 years minimum experience in 
 research organisations or research environments (university\, public polic
 y\, advocacy\, government)\, inclusive of graduate work\; expertise in par
 ticipatory research methods\; a strong track record of seeing research thr
 ough to publication\; a public profile and ability to reach non-academic a
 udiences through writing and speaking\; and the ability to coordinate and 
 conduct in-depth qualitative research. PREFERRED: doctoral degree in infor
 mation science\, education\, social sciences or similar\; established rela
 tionships with relevant organisations in the programme themes\; experience
  with civic engagement or organising in nonprofit\, labour\, advocacy\, re
 search or public interest technology contexts. Reports to the Program Dire
 ctor. Data & Society requires prospective employees to be fully vaccinated
  against COVID-19. TO APPLY: submit a cover letter\, an academic CV\, and 
 the names\, affiliations\, titles\, email addresses and phone numbers for 
 three references by 30 July 2026. Applications are reviewed from 31 July 2
 026. Questions: jobs@datasociety.net. NOTE: this is a salaried job\, not a
  grant or fellowship.\n\nOrganisation: Data & Society Research Institute\n
 Location: Fully remote within the United States. Data & Society is based i
 n New York City and operates as a remote-first organisation\; occasional o
 nsite meetings possible. You must be living and authorised to work in the 
 US\; no visa sponsorship.\nAward: USD 78\,000 to 97\,000 annual salary\, c
 ommensurate with experience\, plus medical\, dental and vision insurance\,
  opt-in insurance and 401k products\, paid time off and paid federal holid
 ays. No application fee.\nDuration: Two-year full-time position\, Septembe
 r 2026 to 31 May 2028\, with no expectation of extension\n\nMore: https://
 job-boards.greenhouse.io/datasocietyresearchinstitute/jobs/8635382002?utm_
 source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://job-boards.greenhouse.io/datasocietyresearchinstitute/jobs/8635
 382002?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Fully remote within the United States. Data & Society is based in 
 New York City and operates as a remote-first organisation\; occasional ons
 ite meetings possible. You must be living and authorised to work in the US
 \; no visa sponsorship.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:lawai-academic-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Law & AI Academic Fellowship
DESCRIPTION:The Institute for Law & AI (LawAI)\, an independent think tank 
 researching and advising on the legal challenges posed by artificial intel
 ligence\, is running its inaugural Law & AI Academic Fellowship for aspiri
 ng legal scholars who intend to go on the US legal academic job market. Th
 e fellowship is designed as an alternative to university-sponsored Visitin
 g Assistant Professor or law fellow positions: fellows spend the majority 
 of their time researching and writing articles for publication in law jour
 nals on the law of transformative AI\, and are prepared for the academic j
 ob market as part of a larger application package. Teaching is not require
 d\, which LawAI frames as a benefit over most university-affiliated positi
 ons\, though fellows who want teaching experience are encouraged to seek i
 t and LawAI and its affiliates may be able to help secure positions. Each 
 fellow is paired with an academic mentor from LawAI's network of affiliate
 d academics for ongoing support\, with more intensive help in the final st
 ages of the job application process including moot interviews and detailed
  feedback. Fellows may also inquire about spending time in residence at ac
 ademic institutions of interest. Candidates are selected in part on how we
 ll their research interests align with LawAI's: the institute expects AI t
 o reshape culture\, the economy\, public policy\, public administration\, 
 politics\, military affairs and geostrategy at least as profoundly as the 
 Industrial Revolution\, and asks whether a candidate's research is well-sc
 oped to changes of that magnitude. Areas of particular interest include ri
 sk regulation of transformative AI\, liability for AI harms\, AI and biose
 curity\, AI and cybersecurity\, executive branch use of transformative AI\
 , national security law\, law and AI infrastructure\, administrative law\,
  constitutional law\, international regulation\, AI in the judiciary\, and
  industrial policy. Full-time two-year role at USD 130\,000 per year\, bas
 ed in Washington DC\, Cambridge UK\, or remote. Applications close 31 July
  2026.\n\nOrganisation: Institute for Law & AI (LawAI)\nLocation: Washingt
 on DC\, USA\; Cambridge\, UK\; or remote\nAward: USD 130\,000 annual salar
 y. No application fee.\nDuration: Two years\, full-time\n\nMore: https://l
 aw-ai.org/career/academic-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdes
 k&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://law-ai.org/career/academic-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnou
 veaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington DC\, USA\; Cambridge\, UK\; or remote
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rand-cast-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260801
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260802
SUMMARY:Deadline: Center on AI\, Security\, and Technology (CAST) Fellowshi
 p
DESCRIPTION:RAND's Center on AI\, Security\, and Technology (CAST) runs a r
 olling fellowship for researchers working on AI security and technology po
 licy\, with mentorship from RAND policy experts. Fellows can be based in W
 ashington DC\, San Francisco or Pittsburgh\, work remotely within the Unit
 ed States\, or be based in the United Kingdom. Terms are flexible: engagem
 ents typically start at six months and can be extended up to three years\,
  full-time or part-time. US fellows receive an annual stipend ranging from
  USD 40\,000 to 200\,000 for full-time work depending on experience\, plus
  a monthly payment that can be put toward health and dental insurance\; UK
  fellows are compensated based on experience. The programme spans career s
 tages from undergraduate through mid-career. ELIGIBILITY: applicants must 
 be based in the US or UK\; US applicants need to be eligible for a governm
 ent security clearance\, and UK applicants must have a current and ongoing
  right to work in the UK. Current RAND staff are not eligible. ROLLING DEA
 DLINE: applications are submitted through an online form and reviewed quar
 terly\, with published cutoffs of 1 February\, 1 May\, 1 August and 1 Nove
 mber\, each answered by the first of the following month. The date recorde
 d here is the next cutoff (1 August 2026)\; the call does not close after 
 it. RAND notes that if one of its listed staff openings matches your inter
 est you should apply to that instead\, and suggests not applying to the fe
 llowship if you have submitted another CAST application within the last si
 x months.\n\nOrganisation: RAND Corporation\, Center on AI\, Security\, an
 d Technology (CAST)\nLocation: Washington DC\, San Francisco or Pittsburgh
 \, USA\, or remote within the United States\; fellows may also be based in
  the United Kingdom\nAward: US fellows: annual stipend from USD 40\,000 to
  200\,000 for full-time fellows depending on experience\, plus a monthly p
 ayment usable for health and dental insurance. UK fellows: compensation ba
 sed on experience. No application fee.\nDuration: Typically starts at 6 mo
 nths\, extendable up to 3 years\; full-time or part-time\n\nMore: https://
 www.rand.org/global-and-emerging-risks/centers/ai-security-and-technology/
 fellows.html?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.rand.org/global-and-emerging-risks/centers/ai-security-and-
 technology/fellows.html?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=r
 eferral
LOCATION:Washington DC\, San Francisco or Pittsburgh\, USA\, or remote with
 in the United States\; fellows may also be based in the United Kingdom
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ai-alignment-foundation-aiaf-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260817
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260818
SUMMARY:Deadline: AIAF Fellowship\, Autumn 2026
DESCRIPTION:An eight-week full-time empirical AI alignment research program
 me run by the AI Alignment Foundation\, with a dedicated research manager\
 , mentorship from senior researchers\, compute and infrastructure\, culmin
 ating in a Demo Day where fellows present their work. Fellows receive a US
 D 12\,000 stipend paid in two installments plus a compute budget. The prog
 ramme is fully remote for the research period\; Demo Day is hybrid in Los 
 Angeles and travel is covered for fellows who attend in person. ELIGIBILIT
 Y: open to all career stages\, including recent PhDs\, graduate students\,
  self-taught researchers and career-changers\, but candidates need a stron
 g machine learning background\, demonstrated engagement with alignment res
 earch\, prior independent research output\, and the ability to work autono
 mously. Non-US applicants are welcome provided they can make Pacific Time 
 meetings\; current graduate students may apply if they can confirm availab
 ility. This is explicitly a technical programme: the foundation says polic
 y-focused applicants should not apply. SELECTION: all applications are rev
 iewed\, qualified candidates advance to a technical test\, and finalists a
 re interviewed\, with decisions expected by early September. Applications 
 close 17 August 2026 (Anywhere on Earth)\; the programme starts 8 Septembe
 r 2026.\n\nOrganisation: AI Alignment Foundation\nLocation: Fully remote f
 or the 8-week research period\; hybrid Demo Day in Los Angeles with travel
  covered for those attending in person. Non-US applicants welcome if avail
 able for Pacific Time meetings.\nAward: USD 12\,000 stipend paid in two in
 stallments\, plus a compute budget. Travel covered for in-person Demo Day 
 attendance. No application fee.\nDuration: 8 weeks full-time at 40 hours p
 er week\, starting 8 September 2026\n\nMore: https://www.aialignmentfounda
 tion.org/fellowship?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://www.aialignmentfoundation.org/fellowship?utm_source=artificialn
 ouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Fully remote for the 8-week research period\; hybrid Demo Day in L
 os Angeles with travel covered for those attending in person. Non-US appli
 cants welcome if available for Pacific Time meetings.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:kennan-institute-digital-fellowship-2026-2027@artificialnouveau.github.
 io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260814
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260815
SUMMARY:Deadline: Kennan Institute Digital Fellowship 2026-2027
DESCRIPTION:The inaugural Kennan Institute Digital Fellowship promotes orig
 inal scholarship and quality non-fiction writing about Russia and the form
 er Soviet Union\, with an emphasis on work that has policy relevance. Ten 
 fellowships are awarded per year\, and AT LEAST FOUR POSITIONS ARE RESERVE
 D FOR RESEARCHERS PURSUING TOPICS IN THE NATURAL SCIENCES\, MEDICINE\, TEC
 HNOLOGY OR RELATED FIELDS\, which is the route by which a technology-focus
 ed project fits this call. The programme aims to give participants time\, 
 professional resources and support while bringing their work to a wider pu
 blic and to the Washington-based policy community\, and to build a cohort 
 network that continues into the alumni body. Each fellow receives a monthl
 y stipend of USD 2\,000\, mentorship and consultation from the Kennan comm
 unity of experts where applicable\, six virtual webinars tailored to the c
 ohort's needs\, and membership of the alumni network. ELIGIBILITY: intende
 d for individuals with several years of experience working on\, studying o
 r otherwise examining Russia and/or broader Eurasia\; applicants must have
  a good working knowledge of English\, as the fellowship is conducted only
  in English and any publications produced for the Kennan Institute appear 
 first in English with possible later translation into regional languages. 
 The programme runs entirely virtually from 1 October 2026 to 31 March 2027
 \; the Institute does not cover travel-related expenses including visas. S
 upported by the Lounsbery Foundation and the U.S. Russia Foundation. Deadl
 ine 14 August 2026\, 17:00 EST. NOTE: 'digital' here describes the virtual
  format\, not the subject matter\, so this fits the desk only if your proj
 ect is itself about technology\, data or science.\n\nOrganisation: Kennan 
 Institute\, Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars (supported by
  the Lounsbery Foundation and the U.S. Russia Foundation)\nLocation: Fully
  virtual. No travel is funded and no travel is required.\nAward: USD 2\,00
 0 monthly stipend for the six-month programme\, plus mentorship from the K
 ennan community of experts\, six virtual webinars tailored to the cohort\,
  and inclusion in the Kennan alumni network of over 4\,500 people. Travel 
 and visa costs are explicitly not covered. No application fee.\nDuration: 
 Six months\, 1 October 2026 to 31 March 2027\, followed by several months 
 of possible integration into the Kennan Institute's event schedule\n\nMore
 : https://www.kennaninstitute.org/digital-fellowship?utm_source=artificial
 nouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.kennaninstitute.org/digital-fellowship?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Fully virtual. No travel is funded and no travel is required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wilson-center-research-fellowship-2027-2028@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260930
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261001
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wilson Center Research Fellowship\, 2027-2028 Class
DESCRIPTION:The Wilson Center\, the congressionally chartered nonpartisan p
 olicy research institution in Washington DC\, awards 10 to 20 research fel
 lowships for its 2027-2028 class. Fellows conduct research and write in th
 eir areas of interest while interacting with policymakers in Washington an
 d with other fellows. The Center accepts policy-relevant\, nonpartisan pro
 posals that address key foreign policy challenges confronting the United S
 tates and the world\, and projects must align with at least one of the Cen
 ter's four scholarship pillars: strategic competition\, economic statecraf
 t\, TECHNOLOGY AND INNOVATION\, and regional scholarship. The technology a
 nd innovation pillar is the relevant route for AI governance\, emerging te
 chnology and digital policy projects\, which the Center also supports thro
 ugh its Science and Technology Innovation Program. Fellows work remotely f
 or the duration of the fellowship\; the Center covers travel costs for two
  required trips to Washington DC at the beginning and the conclusion of th
 e term. The stipend is USD 10\,000 per month for the twelve-month term\, w
 hich runs 1 June 2027 to 30 May 2028. ELIGIBILITY: academic candidates nee
 d a PhD in hand and either a published book or monograph beyond the disser
 tation\, or a substantial body of research articles (five or more) in repu
 table peer-reviewed journals. Non-academic applicants (practitioners\, jou
 rnalists\, public intellectuals) need at least ten years of relevant exper
 ience and a record of substantial policy impact. There is no citizenship r
 estriction\, but English proficiency is required. Applications\, including
  letters of recommendation\, must be submitted online via Interfolio by 11
 :59pm ET on 30 September 2026. Questions: fellowships@wilsoncenter.org. NO
 TE: this is an open-topic foreign policy fellowship\, not an AI-specific o
 ne\; the technology angle depends on how you scope the proposal.\n\nOrgani
 sation: Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars\nLocation: Remote
  for the duration of the fellowship\, with two required trips to Washingto
 n DC (at the start and the end) for which travel costs are covered.\nAward
 : USD 10\,000 per month for a twelve-month fellowship\, plus covered trave
 l for the two required trips to Washington DC. No application fee.\nDurati
 on: Twelve months\, 1 June 2027 to 30 May 2028\n\nMore: https://www.wilson
 center.org/research-fellowship?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_m
 edium=referral
URL:https://www.wilsoncenter.org/research-fellowship?utm_source=artificialn
 ouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote for the duration of the fellowship\, with two required trip
 s to Washington DC (at the start and the end) for which travel costs are c
 overed.
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
